Indonesia Stocks: London Sumatra Indonesia, Medco Energi, Timah

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-08-26T09:19:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-26/indonesia-stocks-london-sumatra-indonesia-medco-energi-timah.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  fell 2.65 points, or 0.1
percent, to 3,841.73, falling for a third day. The gauge has
dropped for a fourth straight week. The market will be closed
for a public holiday next week.  Coal producers: PT Adaro Energy (ADRO IJ),  Indonesia ’s
second-largest coal mining company, fell 3.6 percent to 2,025
rupiah, the lowest close since Oct. 4. PT Borneo Lumbung Energi
& Metal, a coking coal producer, lost 1.7 percent to 1,160
rupiah. CIMB Investment Bank Bhd. downgraded the coal industry
to “neutral” from “overweight,” saying a global economic
slowdown may affect coal prices in the second half of this year.  Palm oil producers: PT Bakrie Sumatera Plantations (UNSP
IJ) declined 2.6 percent to 370 rupiah. PT Astra Agro Lestari
(AALI), the nation’s biggest plantation stock by market value,
lost 1.2 percent to 21,500 rupiah. Palm oil futures dropped as
much as 1.4 percent to 2,953 ringgit ($989) a metric ton in
 Kuala Lumpur , declining for a third day.  PT International Nickel Indonesia (INCO IJ), the nation’s
biggest producer of the metal, rose 4.3 percent to 3,650 rupiah.
Nickel futures gained for a third day, advancing 1.4 percent to
$21,140 a metric ton in  London .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
